column5:
Stimulus 

A condition that requires a response when it arrives at the system
column6:
Environment 

The stimulus occurs under certain conditions. The system may be in an overload condition or in normal operation or some other relevant state
column7:
Response

How the system should respond to the stimulus. The response consists of the responsibilities that the system or the developers should perform in response to the stimulus

column5: TM issues request to observe an imaging SB for MID including reference pointing and SDP responds that the resources are available. SDP is requested to deliver the data to an SKA Regional Centre
column7: The observing commences and the data are ingested, flagged, averaged, direction independent calibration ensues followed by a direction dependent-calibration imaging pipeline. Ultimately a calibrated observatory data product (visibilities, images, catalogues, etc.) is placed into the "staging area" for delivery to SRCs, and archived in the Long Term Storage.

column5: Gravitational wave ToO required large data rate SB to be observed when buffer is full or other resources not available.
column7: Data may have to be discarded from buffer to free up space for ToO SB to commence. ToO SB gets scheduled and Nobel Prize is awarded within 6 months.

column5: A scientist is performing commissioning operations to generate the pointing models for the telescopes. An observation is performed and needs realtime calibration and imaging.
column7: Logging pointing data is processed returning pointing offsets. The SDP commissioning system is used and enables realtime calibration

column5: Observing condition (system status) of current injested observation turns out to be of insufficient quality for science goals. It is continuously of bad quality.
column7: Quality Assessment (QA) identifies bad conditions, problem is easily diagnosable for TM/operator to act upon.

column5: Evolutionary scenario as emerging during the business drivers discussion (COVERED by #1)
New processing library needs to be implemented with very different processing algorithms (MERGED with #1)
column7: Significant testing needs to be done on hardware with many data sets to ensure that processing is bounded and predictable. This is done in parallel with telescope operations. Intermediate outputs can be reviewed and validated.

column5: The stakeholders of SKA want to know if the SDP software produces scientifically valid results. (SDP_REQ-815)
column7: Run a test data set through SDP and compare the result against the result produced by a known software package.

column5: A new Science Pipeline Workflow or algorithm (e.g., Factor and DDFacet) is added (Major change). New processing library needs to be implemented with very different processing algorithms.
column6:
construction, incrementally adding capabilities
Normal Operation
column7:
The Science Pipeline Workflow is implemented along with any necessary additional Processing Component. The workflow is exposed to TM and can be specified at schedule time. SDP correctly schedules the new workflow according to the necessary resources. SKA computing team validates and approves the use of any new pipeline workflows before they go into operations. 
Significant testing is done on hardware with many data sets to ensure that processing is bounded and predictable. This is done in parallel with telescope operations. Intermediate outputs may be reviewed and validated.
Resource utilization models are changed. TM uses the updated models, and subsequent SBs are scheduled using the new models. Data provenance of new data is updated to reflect new workflow/algorithm.

column5: Minor change to pipeline workflow(e.g. fix obvious flaw, add debugging capability etc)
column7: Change can be implemented within a shift and other knock-on activities (provenence, TM change) as well.

column5: SDP is in use, requiring operation at maximum operating capability. An SDP software failure occurs that requires enabling fallback/redundancy measures.
column7: SDP design architecture and reserve capacity enables seamless transition of operations to available redundant capacity.

column5: A processing block (PB) is taking longer than expected to execute.
column7:
In order to not let the PB runaway in an unbounded fashion and impact the upstream observing programme, the PB needs to be terminated.
But what are the decision points in leading to terminating the PB and who does it - under control of SDP or TM?

column5: TM Issues request to observe an SB and SDP does not have sufficient resources available. (MERGED with #4)
column7:
SDP rejects observation and TM rescheduled with another.
Reason for the TM making this request is investigated and resolved.

column5: SDP algorithms have changed. (MERGED with #1 and #6)
column7: Resource utilization models need to be changed. TM uses updated models, and subsequent SBs are scheduled using the new models.

column5: There is a hardware failure which results in data island failure (storage instance and/or processing node fails) or execution engine failure.
column7: Root cause of the failure is identified within 15 minutes. Processing running on the island is gracefully terminated and marked for re-processing when data island becomes available again.

column5: HPC requests SB but resources are not available (MERGED with #4)
The SDP data communication/distribution fails
column7: Recovery mechanisms provided in  the SDP internal data communication  effectively manage errors to a level that SDP critical operation not impacted. Failover works properly  or there is graceful degradation when operating at capacity. Also, consider performance impacts.

column5: Technological (software) upgrade of the Buffer component
column7: The rest of the system is not impacted by the change and Buffer APIs support the new technology with no change

column5: SDP is requested to deliver data to SKA Regional Centre (MERGED with #10)
column7: Viable data is properly delivered in a timely fashion to the appropriate SRC(s).

column5: SKAO staff want to manually update the GSM.
column6: Independent analysis of the sky model parameters for a bright source suggest that these can be optimized.
column7: The SKAO staff should be able to modify the GSM based on their own analysis.

column5: After an observation has been queued for scheduling, a science user requests a change of pipeline processing parameters (pixel resolution, imaging weighting, etc.).
column6: The user realises post scheduling block submission that they would like to optimize their imaging parameters.
column7: Provided that the observation is not currently part of the short-term schedule, it should be possible for the observer to submit a request for a change, provided that the support scientist allocated to the project reviews and accepts the change as being acceptable.

column5: TM (HPC) Issues request to observe an SB. SDP has a processing backlog and, therefore, does not have sufficient resources available.
column6: Normal Operation. Some calibration loops are not converging and therefore SDP is taking longer than expected to finish processing a dataset.
column7: TM checks the short-term schedule for projects that can be observed which are less computationally expensive (e.g., pulsar survey/timing SB). SDP updated resource profile is provided to TM. SDP rejects observation and TM reschedules with another. Reason for the TM making this request is investigated and resolved.

column5: Minor improvement required to a science pipeline workflows
column7: Changes can be made quickly and implemented within a shift. Implementation is validated with well known datasets.

column5: Hardware reaches end of life and needs to be refreshed. For example, Ingest rate/processing rate needs to increase significantly (3 to 5 times). (To save money, this effort may be contracted out.)
column6:
Normal Operation
First refresh of operations environment
column7: New hardware upgrade can be rolled out with minimal impact on operations. Budget is adequate for the next refresh so equipment is added to improve performance with minimal impact to operations.

column5: TM issues request to observe a commensal observation that includes imaging and pulsar SBs and SDP responds that the resources are available. For example, it is decided to schedule several commensal observations on SKA MID, specifically: (a) 1500 pulsar search beams in Band 2 distributed over 4 subarrays with antennas selected from the core ; (b) 16 pulsar timing beams in Band 2 over 4 subarrays (also core); (c) deep Band 5 imaging with the majority of the outer antennas (one subarray); (d) maintenance with 4 antennas in a single subarray; (e) intensity mapping drift scans with the remaining antennas.
column7:
The observing commences and data are ingested. The pulsar data is real time calibrated, the imaging data is independently calibrated with a different pipeline. Ultimately calibrated observatory data products are placed into the "staging area" for delivery to SRCs, and archived in the Long Term Storage.
This application requires computation of multiple independent antenna and beam pointings, delays, delay offsets; communication of pulsar ephemerides, Jones matrices and antenna voltage patterns. Can the system meet latency requirements under these circumstances?

column5: Regional Data Centre connection comes back up after being down for long duration
column7: Telescope continues to observe with data going to LTP. When link is restored data backlog is shipped to regional centres with minimal operator response needed.

column5: An important COTS platform application update required to be deployed for SDP. Final qualification of the update is required before implementation on the operational SDP system. (MERGE with 38)
column7: The SDP application update is effectively qualified. The qualification activities do not result in critical SDP operational downtime

column5: A particular Processing Block (e.g. a pulsar observation, or TOO follow-up) is identified as "somewhat urgent", such that the offline SDP processing is under time pressure (i.e. there is acknowledge scientific benefit if the products can be available quickly is it might lead to furhter TOO triggers or updates to processing plans but it's not absolutely essential).
column7: The "somewhat urgent" SB is successfully executed without any interfering with any other SBs. SDP's off-line scheduling takes into account pre-assigned "importance" when looking for which processing blocks to schedule next. Possibly, when time-domain SBs are underway, a portion of the SDP is specifically set aside to keep pace with this SBs, so that the time domain processing is never allowed to fall more than (e.g. 30 mins) behind  the telescope SB.

column5: Automated QA is performed by SDP which assigns a passing grade to the output data product. SKAO staff reassess the quality of the data and deternine that it is flawed, but the uv data are no longer in the cold buffer.
column7: Scheduling block should be queued for re-observation if there are real issues with the data that are due to problems with the telescope. If the data are poor due to bad weather, the time is lost (TBC).

column5: Construction funding is available, and SDP development begins
column7: Functionality delivered in 3, 6, 9 months. (Understand what notional sequence of capability deliveries are needed.)

column5: Due to  reasons unexpected, demand for SDP data processing and/or internal data communications resources exceeds  nominal designed-for capacity.
column7: SDP fallback/ redundancy features dependent on SDP processing or internal data communications capacity, and which are necessary for maintaining SDP critical availability in the event of a failure, are not compromised.

column5: Ingest rate/processing rate needs to increase significantly (3 to 5 times) (MERGED with #8)
column7: Next refresh includes a significant budget increase so equipment is added and the performance is not impacted

column5: An SDP component malfunctions or degrades.
column7: It is detected by the control system and repairs are initiated. Following repairs to correct a fault, the testing necessary to verify the repaired status can be performed without unacceptable testing downtime implication on users.

column3: Restoration of reporting of Quality Assessment (QA) metrics
column5: Failure of SDP capabilities to report Quality Assessment metrics to Telescope Manager
column7: Reporting of Quality Assessment metrics to Telescope Manager is restored within an acceptable time period, and way, to enable effective assurance of science output quality.

column5: SDP supply is contracted  in accordance with the reliability and maintainability performance estimated/assumed in the SDP CDR RAM and Design reporting.
column7: SDP reliability and maintainability performance complies with the allocations and assumptions applied in the SDP CDR RAM and Design reports, and those allocations and assumptions do enable the SKAO-specified availability for SDP.

column5: An observation is performed and needs realtime calibration and imaging. (MERGE with 47)
column7: The SDP commissioning system is used and enables realtime calibration

column5: A subarray is observing with two groups, cycling between tracking on the science and on calibrator(s). (Scan depends on another scan)
column7: SDP understands which receptors are undertaking which task based on the scanId. The data are processed and ODPs generated successfully.

column5: It is decided to schedule several commensal observations on SKA MID , specifically: (a) 1500 pulsar search beams in Band 2 distributed over 4 subarrays with antennas selected from the core ; (b) 16 pulsar timing beams in Band 2 over 4 subarrays (also core); (c) deep Band 5 imaging with the majority of the outer  (similar to #13?)antennas (one subarray); (d) maintenance with 4 antennas in a single subarray; (e) intensity mapping drift scans with the remaining antennas. (MERGED with #13)
column7: This application requires computation of multiple independent antenna and beam pointings, delays, delay offsets; communication of pulsar ephemerides, Jones matrices and antenna voltage patterns. Can the system meet latency requirements under these circumstances?

column5: Technological upgrades lead to replace openstack with a different technology. (MERGE with 38 and 25)
column7: Successfully upgrade to new technology within X.

column5: A new SRC (multiple drop off points are added) is added to the network
column7: Data is delivered to the new SRC and long term archive data is balanced across SRCs. Data can be found by astronomers in the new SRC.

column5: Unauthorized user maliciously tries to access meta data or data products
column7: user is prevented from accessing the meta data or data products

column5: Denial of Service attack is attempted on internet facing interface
column7: DoS is prevented

column5: A schedule block completes execution. The next schedule block requires standard imaging mode with QA feedback and calibration feedback for LOW. (same as #10? Do we want separate scenarios for MID & LOW?)) Probably too similar to #10, so downgraded to L.
column7: Execution of the new schedule block starts and observation data collection begins on schedule. Processing block is started when resources become available.

column5: Operating system version  or Openstack or other technology requires upgrade on all SDP hardware.
column7: The system can be upgraded in reasonable time while maintaining the SDP availability to the telescope. The SDP application update is effectively qualified. The qualification activities do not result in critical SDP operational downtime

column5: It is necessary to run Factor (or something with same features) on an observation, and therefore it needs to be mapped to the SDP architecture. (Like #1, but more specific) (MERGED with #1)
column7: SDP is flexible enough to make this happen. The platform does not need to change substantially to run Factor, although possibly with some small changes to Factor.

column5: Same as 43 but for DDFacet (MERGED with #1)
column7: Idem as 43

column5: SKA needs portability of SDP to SRCs and mixed software environments. Portability to environments without TM and CSP could enable deployment/development of SDP at other locations or for other purposes. (SDP_REQ-812, merge with 813)
column6: Minimal set of fairly standard COTS hardware platforms at SRCs (even though SDP may run on something that is not standard).
column7: SDP is deployed at SRC or mixed use environment without changes to SDP software providing SRCs have a compatible hardware configuration (i.e., a reasonably equipped datacentre). SDP may only support a minimal set COTS hardware platforms (incl accelerators, etc.) and a minimal set of software stacks (e.g. OpenStack)

column5: For all imaging observations, it appeared that more iterations in the direction-dependent calibration <-> imaging loop are required and more directions need to be solved for to obtain science-quality results as that was anticipated.
column7: SDP will still succesfully process such observations, but on a best effort basis. The scheduling system and processing architecture is flexible enough to cope with this.

column5: Config database goes down.
column7: It is brought back up without major impact to operations.

column5: The N-1 antenna data appears incorrect.
column7: Scientists and operators can view intermediate data to support debugging.

column5: Unmonitored entity (i.e., component) needs to be monitored.
column7: It  is inserted into the system to be monitored easily and quickly and is properly monitored.

column5: An urgent COTS application update needs to be deployed.
column7: The SDP application update is effectively qualified ASAP. The qualification activities do not result in critical SDP operational downtime

column5: Scientist who wasn't PI needs to understand the exact data provenence or published data.
Migrate to Python 5
column7: SDP is migrated to Python 5 within a short period of time and there are no operational impacts.
